instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system is orchestrated around the Digital Shadow Reference Model, which is expressed as a UML class diagram. Core elements are Assets (physical components), Models (engineering, simulation, or data‑calculation models), Processing Components (software services that consume input data traces and produce derived data traces), and Data Traces themselves. Concretization maps these abstract concepts to concrete classes and relations, establishing a component‑centric architecture where each Processing Component encapsulates a specific computational function (e.g., simulation, data aggregation) and maintains traceability through the ‘originates‑from’ association. This structure enables systematic integration of heterogeneous models and tools (e.g., Simulink, C++, Java) and supports resource management by assigning processing workloads to dedicated computational units. System‑wide coordination is achieved by chaining Processing Components via data‑trace dependencies, allowing transitive traceability and coherent execution across the whole Twin."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin lifecycle follows the MBSE development flow described in Document 1: (1) Requirements stage, where high‑level functional requirements are captured; (2) Functional‑architecture stage, modelled with SysML requirement and block diagrams; (3) Logical‑architecture stage, expressed with ADLs such as ACME, AADL, MontiArc, describing components, interfaces and connectors; (4) Product/technical stage, where the logical model is concretized into engineering models (Simulink, C++/Java code) and simulation models. Transition between stages is managed by conformance relations to the reference model (Document 2) and by concretization mappings that instantiate abstract concepts with concrete elements. Governance involves traceability of data traces back to processing components and models as defined in the Digital Shadow Reference Model."
]

